    <Folder>
      <name>Season 7</name>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Mad Dog Motorcycle Club Philippines</name>
        <description>Tony watched cover bands at this biker bar</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1517-A52714</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            121.0304999,14.5623486,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Jollibee Bluebay Walk</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony loves this local fast food joint, even though he said "I hate myself" as he was finishing his meal. He had Jolly Spaghetti (with hot dogs in it) and Chicken Joy with a brown sauce.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1530-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            120.9919794,14.5373546,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Pearl Garden Hotel</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony crashed a holiday party here, the Seven Continents Travel & Tours corporate Christmas party. They had lechon, a whole pig roast pork that is traditional during the holidays.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1602-FF5252</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            120.9851761,14.5726019,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Alvie</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony had halo halo, which translates to "mix mix." It is an "icy, milky, technicolor concoction of sundry sweet mung beans, candied fruits, and gelatins." Also has banana, condensed milk, and sweet young coconut.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            120.976289,14.588422,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Super Six</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony came here to eat his favorite Filipino street food, which he describes as "possibly the best thing you can ever eat with a cold beer." The dish he is talking about is sisig, a sizzling dish of pig face with a runny egg on top.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            120.9855797,14.5700429,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Oarhouse Pub of Manila</name>
        <description>Tony met with journalist Mark Navales to have drinks at this bar.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1517-A52714</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            120.9854587,14.5728208,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Meal with locals</name>
        <description>Tony met with the local band Keystone. They made him the national dish, adobo. They had adobo with pork and chicken.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1603-9C27B0</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            121.0222565,14.6090537,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Meal with a local</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony had another meal with a local, the nanny of one of the show's directors, Erik Osterholm. She made kare kare, or oxtail soup. After living abroad for over 30 years, Aurora is finally back home living with her kids and grandchildren, although many still live abroad to send money home to support the family. They talked about the sacrifices Aurora and many other Filipinos make to send money for better lives for these poor families.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1603-9C27B0</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            121.0222565,14.6090537,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Old Town Ale House</name>
        <description>Tony had a beer here with the owner of the bar. The owner also creates X-rated drawings of famous people and hangs them on the wall, including political figures, athletes, actors</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1879-FFD600</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -87.6355948,41.9110059,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Valois Restaurant</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Cafeteria style restaurant where Tony ordered meatloaf and macaroni & cheese. He ate there with Bruce Cameron Elliott, who owns the Old Town Ale House. Bruce told Tony that he often saw Barack Obama having breakfast at this restaurant]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -87.5883097,41.7996635,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>The Second City</name>
        <description>Legendary improv comedy theater where John Belushi, Gilda Radner, and others got their start.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1614-FF5252</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -87.6349957,41.9116067,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name><![CDATA[Longman & Eagle]]></name>
        <description>Tony ate here with comedian Paul Jurewicz. They had beef tartare, roasted bone marrow, tete de cochon with blue cheese and celery relish, confit of beef tripe, slow roasted cauliflower with caramelized onions and lentils.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -87.7071462,41.9300853,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Sze Chuan Cuisine</name>
        <description>Tony ate here with Chef Stephanie Izard and Chef Peter Wong. They had pork dumplings in chili oil, mapo doufu, and fish hotpot.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -87.632201,41.8486483,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name><![CDATA[Lunch at Lupe Fiasco's home]]></name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony had a meal at Chicago-based rapper Lupe Fiasco's house with his extended family. His mother made macaroni and cheese, collard greens, and other soul food.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1603-9C27B0</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -87.6297982,41.8781136,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name><![CDATA[Ricobene's]]></name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony met with musician, producer, and sound engineer Steve Albini. They had the famous breaded steak sandwich, which Tony said was "at least 4 pounds" and required lots of napkins.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -87.6338374,41.8457679,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Topo Gigio Ristorante</name>
        <description>Tony had veal saltimbocca with Bruce Cameron Elliott and a pal from the Old Town Ale House whose nickname is Buzzkill. They discussed the Cubs and White Sox rivalry. His dining companions had scallops in pesto cream sauce and squid ink pasta with shrimp.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -87.6348276,41.9096739,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>The Ocean Club</name>
        <description>Not sure if this is the beach bar where Tony had some raki to start the day. It was a ocean side bar near where the boat dropped them off.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1517-A52714</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            25.374604,37.103375,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Souvlucky</name>
        <description>Tony had lunch with local fisherman and discussed the economy. They had souvlaki, fries, and other Mediterranean goodies, and Mythos beer.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            25.3585183,37.0593117,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Bluefin divers Naxos Diving Center-Padi 5 Star Resort</name>
        <description>Tony took a diving tour to see a sunken ship that sunk in 1982.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1861-FF5252</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            25.3522859,37.0732492,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Taverna Platanos</name>
        <description>Naxos style pork called rosto in a small village in the mountains.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            25.5204977,37.0714997,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Meal with locals</name>
        <description>Tony ate with a family on a local farm, including the Aegan governor. They had stuffed peppers, slow-cooked rooster, rabbit in a wine sauce, and potatoes.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1566-9C27B0</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            25.5202366,37.0713328,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Μαρίνα Νάξου / Naxos Dock</name>
        <description>Tony had a meal on a boat with some fishermen. They had octopus, grilled salatouri (skate), marinated anchovies, grilled rofos (grouper), and mashed fava beans.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1681-9C27B0</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            25.374459,37.104565,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Medicine Tail Coulee</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony met with Crow indian Kennard Real Bird, who ranches horses in the same location where General Custer "had the worst day of his life." There is also Indian relay racing, a dangerous sport involving jumping from moving horses.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1601-FF5252</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -107.4156389,45.5469174,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name><![CDATA[Lydia's Supper Club]]></name>
        <description>Tony had pickled beets, sweet potato salad, salami and cheese, side salad, pickled peppers, breadsticks, large scallops in white wine sauce, extra thick tenderloin of beef</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -112.5086111,45.9491667,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Silver Dollar Saloon</name>
        <description>Tony discussed the history of Butte as a union town with former congresswoman, Amanda Curtis</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1879-FFD600</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -112.5356953,46.0114251,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Orphan Boy Mine</name>
        <description>Tony did some mining with miners.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1627-FF5252</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -112.5386339,46.0110375,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Montana Pheasants Forever</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony went hunting with a guide and stand-up comedian Joe Rogan. They cooked bird they shot over a fire, with a conservationist and a journalist from Field & Stream.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1812-FF5252</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -113.998364,46.842721,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Mint Bar and Grill</name>
        <description>Tony had beers at this bar that opened in the 1920s.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1879-FFD600</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -110.5599505,45.6615785,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name><![CDATA[Meal at Jim Harrison's house]]></name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony ate with renowned poet Jim Harrison, who also wrote books about food. Jim's friend Dan cooked some spatchcock Hungarian partridge, liver loaf with elk meat, beets, quail in aspic, elk carpacchio, smoked trout.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-9C27B0</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -110.5599556,45.6614105,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name><![CDATA[Clouds Bar & Restaurant]]></name>
        <description>Tony and Zamir met up at this bar on the top floor of the Radisson to drink chacha, a traditional Georgian moonshine</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1517-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            41.6376312,41.6535627,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Peace Casino</name>
        <description>Tony and Zamir gambled (and lost) at this casino. They played blackjack and roulette.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1540-FF5252</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            41.630888,41.651103,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name><![CDATA[Dilber Gentlemen's Club]]></name>
        <description>Tony and Zamir went to this strip club after they lost money at gambling.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1713-FF5252</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            41.6314345,41.6411317,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Sazandari</name>
        <description><![CDATA["One of the city's older, more traditional joints" Tony said. Tony and Zamir are both hungover from the previous evening's shenanigans. They had a hangover cure, khashi which Zamir explained is made of beef broth from bones and joints. Tony did not think it worked. He did enjoy the chashushuli, "a stew of slow-cooked veal with onion and tomato, heavily seasoned with coriander, fennel, garlic, and chilies."]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            41.621686,41.643872,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Gabriadze</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony ate here with Paul Rimple, Tbilisi bureau chief for Culinary Backstreets. They had "salad with orange, almonds, and honey; grilled lamb ribs with pomegranate sauce; slices of fried eggplant wrapped around a walnut filling; chkmeruli, chicken slow-baked in an oven and then simmered in garlic and milk."]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            44.806565,41.6956983,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Sofia Melnikovas Fantastiuri Duqani</name>
        <description>Tony had a meal with activist and journalist Tamara Chergoleishvili, founding director of Georgia’s Tabula Media. They had khinkali which Tony describes as “big, fat, juicy soup dumplings filled with spicy cumin-jacked minced beef in a hot, rich, potentially scalding broth”.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            44.7988159,41.6998602,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Culinarium (moved)</name>
        <description>Tony ate here with chef Tekuna Gachechiladze, who is trying to modernize Georgian cuisine. I have also mapped the current location of this restaurant.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-757575</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            44.803142,41.6914304,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Culinarium Khasheria</name>
        <description><![CDATA[New site of chef Tekuna Gachechiladze's restaurant.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            44.8105858,41.6880664,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Patara Khurvaleti</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony headed out to this border agrarian town of only 9 families, to have a traditional supra. A supra is a Georgian feast. Tony ate with journalist Dima Bit-Suleiman, and Ushangi & Makvala Kokashvili. They had three varieties of khachapuri, a traditional cheese-filled bread, stuffed here with potato, beet leaves, or stewed cabbage; korma made from a roasted pig; homemade bread.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-9C27B0</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            44.30034,42.0521471,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name><![CDATA[Pheasant's Tears Winery]]></name>
        <description>The chef, Gia Rokashvili, uses local ingredients and serves the food with local wines. Tony had boiled beets in wild plum sauce, freshly foraged mushrooms with chili pepper, mint, and tarragon; baby lamb stewed with cumin, cooked with wild rice; fresh tonis puri, bread made in a tandoor-like clay oven. He ate with Keti Bochorishvili, former Deputy Minister of Economy and Sustainable Development, and Tamuna Gvaberidze, gallery owner.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            45.920273,41.6161284,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Meal with locals</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony had a meal prepared by Meriko Gubeladze, a star chef at Tbilisi’s Black Lion Restaurant. They had spinach with walnuts and wild capers; pickled carrots; cheese curds with roasted hazelnuts and mint; roasted eggplant seasoned with coriander; kharcho, a stewed chicken cooked slow with ajika chili sauce, onions, marigold flower powder, and blue fenugreek, and cooked & served in a pumpkin.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-9C27B0</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            44.6975318,41.6986768,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Marche Kermel</name>
        <description>Tony met at this bustling food market with NPR West Africa correspondent Ofeibea Quist-Arcton.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1578-673AB7</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -17.4287765,14.6705731,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Meal with locals</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Not sure if this is the correct location. Tony said the beach was called "Coeur. de Cassazione" but I could not find this on the map. He ate with Pierre Thiam, a renowned chef and cookbook author. They had yassa, made with a local fish called ciof, "cooked simply on the bone, wrapped in foil, and steamed over the fire, served with a mignonette style sauce with onions; grilled mussels, sea urchin."]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-9C27B0</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -17.4755427,14.6987646,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Huitres De Sokone</name>
        <description>Tony met with a group of women (Fama Diof, photographer; Umi Nador, journalist and TV presenter; Minyel Tal, entrepreneur) to discuss gender roles in a mostly Muslim country. They ate clams, sea urchins, and thiof fish.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -17.5288871,14.7458367,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Restaurant le BAZOFF</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony watched local musician Youssou N’Dour perform at this restaurant. They also ate beef mafe served with rice, a stew thickened with ground peanuts. Tony says, "there are similar preparations throughout West Africa, but the Senegalese version is particularly great."]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -17.4601211,14.7060052,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Boulangerie SMBIS</name>
        <description>Tony had a street food dish called ndambe, a spread of spicy lentils on a baguette. You buy the baguette from this bakery, then go to the woman on the street who has the lentils to spread on it.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -16.504029,16.027779,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Meal with locals</name>
        <description>Tony had a meal with locals. They ate mulet farci, a stuffed baked local fish called mullet, stuffed with bread and vegetables and baked.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-9C27B0</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -16.4818167,16.0326307,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name><![CDATA[Le jardin de l'Amitié]]></name>
        <description>Tony met with a group of entrepreneurs to discuss the economy of Senegal to have drinks.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1879-FFD600</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -17.4612159,14.7024483,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Dibiterie Le Mboté</name>
        <description>Tony ate with rapper Djily Bagdad. They ate dibi, roasted meat served on paper with grilled onions and mustard.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -17.4518121,14.6769012,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Lac Rose</name>
        <description><![CDATA[The pink lake, as it is called, is a site for harvesting salt, but is also known as the finish line "for a legendary trans-African endurance race." Tony sat with a driver as they did some offroading then had a meal together.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1661-FF5252</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -17.2341324,14.8387836,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Meal with locals</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony ate the Senegal national dish with some locals. The national dish is called ceebu jen (meaning rice with fish). The fish they used was "Senegalese grouper, scored and stuffed with a mixture of garlic, parsley, and peppers, then slow simmered in a hearty tomato broth, infused by a funkatizing goodness brought by fermented conch and salt fish, served over rice and vegetables." ]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-9C27B0</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -17.4676861,14.716677,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Brauerei zur Malzmühle</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony met with Heinz Grüne, beer expert, to have some kolsch, a style of pale ale created in Cologne. They ate a halve hahn, "Gouda cheese on rye" and Mettbrötchen, or raw minced pork on a roll. They also had himmel und erde (blood sausage, fried onions, mashed potatoes, applesauce), and cured pork]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1879-FFD600</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            6.9605228,50.9347183,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Bei Oma Kleinmann</name>
        <description>Tony met with Tracey Gudwin (friend and former producer for No Reservations) and Anke Lönne, a resident of Cologne. They had schnitzel, which Bourdain describes as “surfboard-sized slabs of veal and pork filled with many wonderful things, dredged in breadcrumbs and fried in magical, magical deep fat.”</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            6.9383544,50.9295329,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Artistanbul Restaurant</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony met with Melek Yaprak, aTurkish-German whose grandparents were among the first wave of Turkish immigrants in Cologne in this Turkish restaurant. They had Raki and mezze of "spicy mashed vegetables, tzatziki, hummus, beetroot and olive dip, fried eggplant, pastries with feta, meatballs with tomato sauce and mint"]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            6.9515457,50.9415662,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name><![CDATA[Ox & Klee]]></name>
        <description>Tony met with former rock star Irmin Schmidt of the Krautrock band Can. They had grilled scalllop with black salsify served with a consomme of burned hay, lemon gelee, and walnut oil; grilled lobster with a dashi of eel, marinated algae, fermented kale, and yuzu froth; braised ox cheeks with marrow, beet roots with mustard, gratin potatoes, black truffle.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            6.9656148,50.9275031,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>De Fressbud</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony met with the chef from Ox & Klee, Daniel Gottschlich and his friend Demetri to have grilled bratwurst with curry sauce.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            6.9569132,50.948102,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Kleine Glocke</name>
        <description><![CDATA["A hangout for Cologne's artist community since the first World War." Tony ate sauerbraten (pot roast of horse meat) with chef René Stessl]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            6.950026,50.9385719,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Uerige</name>
        <description>Serving beer and pork products since 1862. Tony met with Heinz and his friend Judith drank alt (a dark beer) and ate pickled eggs, cabbage and mettwurst, and spicy pork goulash with rye bread.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            6.7722509,51.2249992,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Bar Trattoria Celentano</name>
        <description>Tony had a meal with Maurizio Arca, a Sardinian-German. They had wine, antipasti (carpaccio, tomatoes with pepper and parmesan, grilled zucchini, mortadella), spaghetti with white clam sauce</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            6.9534868,50.9502977,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Habibi Köln</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony met with Syrian immigrant Sakher Al Mohamad to talk about the unrest Cologne faced when middle eastern terrorists attacked Cologne residents on New Year's Eve 2015.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            6.937699,50.929575,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Don Carlos</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony had a meal with Argentina's most famous chef, Francis Mallmann. They ate empanadas, grilled beef, and blood sausage]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -58.363669,-34.6361033,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Los Talas del Entrerriano</name>
        <description>Tony met with therapist Marianna and had parrilla, a traditional Argentine meal called achuras, including kidney, chorizo, morcilla.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -58.5697087,-34.5191299,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Bar Sur</name>
        <description>Tony met with a career server named Mario and had drinks and snacks.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -58.3701096,-34.6183371,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Club GON</name>
        <description>Tony came to this soccer club to drink beer and eat chorizo with Chef Soledad Nardelli, and watch kitchen staff of 2 rival restaurants play soccer at 1 am</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1696-FF5252</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -58.4179207,-34.6272462,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Meal with locals</name>
        <description>Tony met with Nico (lead singer of band Octafonic) to have a meal at a construction site. In Argentina, construction workers often have barbecued beef together at work once a week. </description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-9C27B0</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -58.3815591,-34.6036844,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
    </Folder>
    <Folder>
      <name>Season 8</name>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Bún ốc Giang phố cổ</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony started this Vietnam journey at this bún ốc restaurant in Hanoi's Old Quarter. Bún ốc is a snail noodle soup]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1640-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            105.8517253,21.034871,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Bánh Cuốn Nóng Kim Thoa</name>
        <description>Tony met with Thao Griffiths, the country director of the Vietnam Foundation. They ate Banh cuon, a dish of ground pork with wood ear mushroom in a thin rice noodle roll that is dipped in broth.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            105.8580136,21.0320255,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Bún Chửi Ngô Sĩ Liên</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Also known as "Cussing Noodles" due to the owner yelling at people, but is Tony's friend Ha Pham's favorite place to get bún chin zou, or as Tony describes, "a glorious steaming bowl of rice noodles with spicy chilies, a rich hearty porky broth with pig's knuckles and snout. It's the only item on the menu and it's good!"]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1640-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            105.8387278,21.0269386,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Bia Hải Xồm</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony met with his old friend Dinh Hoang Linh, his former Foreign Affairs Ministry minder. "Bia Hảirefers to the roadside joints where locals gather to enjoy keg dispensed, freshly brewed draft beer]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1879-FFD600</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            105.8112144,21.0343372,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Hạ Long Bay</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony took a boat ride aboard the Emeraude to this bay, one of Vietnam's most visited destinations. "Hạ Long means 'where the dragon descends into the sea' and legend says that this is where a great dragon charged, protecting Vietnam from foreign invaders."]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1681-FF5252</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            107.0448069,20.9711977,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Bún chả Hương Liên</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony met with President Obama (while he was in office) to have bún chả. It was Obama's first visit to Vietnam, and it reminded him of his childhood visits to Indonesia. They shared cold beers and bún chả, a traditional Vietnamese soup of grilled pork belly, pork patties, and noodles served in a broth of vinegar, sugar, fish sauce and served with chilies. Obama told a story about a city in Indonesia called Puncak where he would eat at a roadside restaurant overlooking the tea fields, with a river running through the restaurant. You could pick a fish and they'd fry it and serve it with a bed of rice. Obama said it was a simple meal but his favorite.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1640-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            105.8538968,21.0181355,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Meal with locals</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Chef friends put together a meal with local seasonal ingredients: "90-day aged ribeye steaks from nearby Bear Creek Farms... topped off with oyster mushrooms and bourbon soy, and some nice runny eggs, and garlic. Grits, greasy beans, homemade ricotta with a cold smoked sausage, and roasted acorn squash.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-9C27B0</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -86.7816016,36.1626638,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name><![CDATA[Dino's Bar]]></name>
        <description><![CDATA[A burger joint that is also a hangout for Nashville musicians. They had burgers and hot fries (smothered with cheese and hot chicken flavor), which Tony called "country poutine."]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1530-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -86.7492939,36.1811464,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name><![CDATA[Dandgure's Classic Southern Cooking]]></name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony went to this cafeteria style restaurant with Jesse Boyce (songwriter/producer),and ordered a combo popular in Nashville called the "meat & three" which includes a meat dish and 3 sides. Tony chose fried chicken with okra, corn, and mashed potatoes. ]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -86.7755676,36.1534484,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name><![CDATA[Bolton's Spicy Chicken & Fish]]></name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony tried the hottest version of Nashville Hot Chicken (and paid dearly for it later). He ate with Allison Mosshart of the band The Kills and her brother Matthew, a chef. He said he had a 12-hour "existentially awful experience" after eating the chicken.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -86.7613955,36.1740488,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Music City Cryo</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony went here with Dean Fertita (guitarist and keyboard player for Queens of the Stone Age, musician with the Dead Weather). "Cryotherapy, the latest in muscle recovery treatments," explains Tony. Liquid nitrogen chills down the pod to -300 degrees which causes your body to kickstart anti-inflammatory proteins.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1697-0288D1</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -86.7973939,36.1169936,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>City House</name>
        <description>Chef Tandy Wilson made pizza for Tony and Dean Fertita (guitarist and keyboard player for Queens of the Stone Age, musician with the Dead Weather).</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1651-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -86.787262,36.176923,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Third Man Records</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony went to The Blue Room to watch singer-songwriter Margo Price record directly to acetate at Jack White's studio.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1614-F57C00</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -86.7779837,36.1521981,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Meal with locals</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony visited singer-songwriter Margo Price's home where her musician friends had a party and prepared food. Her husband and bass player in the band, Jeremy, made biscuits topped with pimento cheese and bacon; braised short rib on crostini with goat cheese.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1603-9C27B0</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -86.7422102,36.1966714,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>The Patterson House</name>
        <description>Cocktail bar with a mixologist. Upstairs there is a restaurant called Catbird Seat. Tony had a drink here before he ate a meal at the restaurant.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1517-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -86.7940805,36.1512784,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>The Catbird Seat</name>
        <description>20-seat restaurant with a menu that changes nightly. They ate risotto with sunflower seeds instead of rice, topped with fermented sunchokes and garnished with sunflower sprouts; linguini with sea urchin and chili flakes, made with Japanese ingredients—wakame bucatini, yuzukoshō to represent the chili flakes, scallops dried and smoked and grated over the top; macaron and cookie.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -86.7941007,36.1512805,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name><![CDATA[Party at Alison Mosshart's house]]></name>
        <description><![CDATA[Dead Weather and The Kills both performed at this house party. Tony and Matthew (Alison's chef brother) cooked a bunch of food including apple walnut salad, fried pork dumplings, pulled pork with red cabbage, brisket, and deviled eggs because "it ain't a party without deviled eggs."]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1637-9C27B0</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -86.7816016,36.1626638,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Pinewood Social</name>
        <description><![CDATA[The day after the big party at Alison's house, they went to get bloody marys and mimosas at this bowling alley with brunch food.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -86.7677778,36.1583833,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Xiaomingtang Dandantian Shuimian</name>
        <description><![CDATA[For Tony and Eric Ripert's first place, they had dan dan tian shui mian.(spicy noodles) from this place.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1640-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            104.060424,30.658848,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Tiantian Restaurant</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony and Eric ate at this sichuan restaurant, and Eric said the spice was "challenging" They had pickled chicken feet, la zi ji (spicy chicken), mapo tofu (Tony's favorite), tong jiao yu (Sichuan green-peppercorn fish)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1640-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            104.065166,30.6272866,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Leshan Giant Buddha</name>
        <description>Tony and Eric took a boat ride to see the largest stone buddha in the world, built in 713. </description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1668-FF5252</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            103.7715369,29.5441309,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Lianglukou Hotpot</name>
        <description><![CDATA[By the end of this meal of painfully spicy Sichuan hot pot (dog tail; tripe, or “thousand-layer stomach”; tofu skin, seaweed, various meats and fishes, intestines), Eric said he couldn't think anymore (because of the spice). Tony enjoyed the meal and watching Eric squirm.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            120.784871,30.753309,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Yu Zhilan Restaurant (Closed?)</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Not sure if this restaurant is still here. Tony and Eric met with Fuchsia Dunlop, a James Beard award-winning writer and cook who specializes in Chinese cuisine. They had "lily buds scented with rosebuds, thinly sliced beef shank with chili oil, tea tree mushrooms blanched and lightly stir-fried, prawns served cold with homemade noodles dressed with natural vegetable extracts, noodles hand-cut with duck-egg yolks, braised sea cucumber."]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-BDBDBD</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            104.0587669,30.666744,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Qingshui River</name>
        <description>Tony and Eric took a train out to Long Teng Dong Jie to eat a meal with Chen Zhong, a filmmaker. </description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-9C27B0</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            107.092513,27.201443,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>St John Restaurant</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony ate here with food critic Jay Rayner. Tony describes how highly he regards this restaurant, "The food that I yearn for is food that I react to in an entirely emotional way. I'm looking for a suspension of logic and reason. This is something that I got here from the beginning." They had "roast bone marrow with parsley and caper salad, sourdough made here" along with "pickled calves' tripe with radish, shaved carrot, and watercress; skate poached in court-bouillon, with fennel in green sauce of fresh parsley, herbs, and anchovies; pan seared kidney in savory sauce served on toast; pig’s head and potato pie."]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -0.1014304,51.5204534,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Princess Victoria</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony met with legendary cookbook author Nigella Lawson to have some Scotch eggs, whitebait ("tiny baby herring lightly battered whole and fried, tossed with a little bit of lemon juice and salt"), fries, and Guinness.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -0.2408907,51.5064194,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Rudloe Arms Hotel By Marco Pierre White</name>
        <description><![CDATA[An inn and a restaurant. Tony and Chef Marco Pierre White had "a pan-roasted filet of beef with escargot; pig's trotter a la Pierre Koffman. The chef raises the pigs on the grounds of the inn.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-7CB342</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -2.226556,51.4305518,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name><![CDATA[Pepper & Spice Restaurant London]]></name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony met with Jamie Hince, "half the creative alliance that makes up the band The Kills." This is Jamie's "favorite local joint for Caribbean food"]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -0.0775277,51.5462421,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Chequers Inn</name>
        <description><![CDATA["Artist, author, icon, Ralph Steadman continues to make art every day. He was the visual expression of Hunter S. Thompson's work." Tony met with Steadman at this restaurant/pub for lunch. "Runny egg wrapped in Parma ham and breadcrumbs, prawn cocktail, fish & chips with mushy peas, steak & stilton pie"]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            0.5172639,51.2405456,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Marlboro</name>
        <description>Tony met with Chef Marco Pierre for deep fried haddock, mushy peas, and a chip butty.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1573-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -2.4550661,50.6077706,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Rochelle Canteen</name>
        <description>Tony met with the chef, Margo Henderson. They had wine, peas in their pods, radishes, vitello tonnato, Welsh lamb chops with lentils and green sauce.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -0.0742918,51.5257669,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>The Hunter S</name>
        <description>Tony had some Guinness.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1879-FFD600</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -0.0835358,51.545934,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name><![CDATA[Breakfast at Nigella's house]]></name>
        <description>Tony was hungover so Nigella cooked Eggs in Purgatory for him, bread toasted in beef fat, served with runny eggs and spicy chili tomato sauce. </description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-9C27B0</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -0.1277583,51.5073509,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Margaret Long Wisdom High School</name>
        <description>Tony visited this high school when it was called Robert E. Lee Senior High School. It is the most ethnically diverse school in Houston, with 80% of students speaking a language other than English as their first language.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1682-0097A7</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -95.5140823,29.7233786,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Meal with locals</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony went to Principal Jonathan Nguyen Trinh's home to have lunch. They had tamales de gallina; fresh pupusas on the grill; a jellyfish, shrimp, and pork dish tossed with mint, peanuts, carrots, red onion, and dressed with fish sauce; mi quang: a Vietnamese noodle dish made with pork ribs, shrimp, and chilies; and “Viet-bayou style” crawdads steamed with sriracha, orange juice, and beer]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1603-9C27B0</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -95.2860474,29.5635666,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Burns Original BBQ</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony had not been back in 15 years. He ordered "the torpedo-sized baked potato filled with cheddar cheese and chopped barbecue beef, and homemade link sausage. Slow cooked pork ribs, big ass beef ribs, and brisket."]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -95.4209593,29.8769751,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>The Point</name>
        <description>The Vietnamese owners fulfill a niche of the community, serving Vietnamese and Mexican food. Pho (brisket, eye round, meatball, tripe, and tendon); shrimp ceviche; tacos with eggs, jalapenos, tomatoes.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -96.2102376,28.7054693,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name><![CDATA[Acapulco Ballroom & Bridal Shop]]></name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony crashed a Quinceañera held here and talked with the owners about the "quince" culture in the Houston area.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1511-FF5252</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -95.1944251,29.6980281,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name><![CDATA[La Guadalupana Bakery & Cafe]]></name>
        <description><![CDATA[A traditional Mexican and Tex-Mex restaurant. Tony ate Machaca Nortena ("marinated beef that's been pounded, rubbed with spices, then dried and shredded") and Migas (eggs mixed with fried and chopped corn tortillas).]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -95.4020023,29.746827,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Plant It Forward (Warehouse)</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Plant It Forward farmers Gertrude and Albert Lombo and Gimoule and Constant Ngouala hosted a meal with Tony and other friends. They had "slow-cooked stew of sausage, shrimp, dried mackerel, and Malabar spinach over fufu; then Texas beef brochettes marinated in chilies and cilantro  and Maggi bouillon with a ratatouille made from produce grown right here."]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1566-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -95.4433233,29.6650135,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Sardar Patel Stadium</name>
        <description>Tony met with Kuldeep Patel, league president of the Houston Indian Cricket Club, and other local cricket players. They watched a game and then ate tandoori chicken, curried goat, and potato masala dosas.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1554-FF5252</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -95.7016146,29.6614904,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Masa</name>
        <description><![CDATA[America's most expensive restaurant, it costs around $600 per person. It is run by Masa Takayama, America's most respected sushi chef. Tony traveled Japan with Masa.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -73.9830458,40.7685299,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Ōmichō Market</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony and Masa ate fresh seafood at this market. They had sea urchin, kanogani (snow crab), grilled eel livers, and giant oysters "as big as freakin' clown shoes"]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1573-673AB7</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            136.6568157,36.5712847,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Higashi Chaya District</name>
        <description>Tony and Masa watched a geiko perform at Fujinoya Tea House (could not find exact location on map).</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1611-FF5252</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            136.6669859,36.5725048,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Yamanoo</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Traditional kaiseki restaurant that dates back to 1890. Menu changes as seasonal ingredients become available. ""Preserved in a tightly wrapped bamboo leaf, intended to resemble a sword, sea bream served chimaki-style over rice slightly sweetened by vinegar, soy sauce, sugar, and sesame... Grilled rockfish made Horaku style, steamed in smoking wormwood. Bamboo shoots and wagyu beef prepared tableside with soy sauce and mirin. Today's sashimi course is cod, salted and pressed between leaves of kelp for 2 hours, coated with sake-cured codfish roe. Next to it, flounder, its skin gently rubbed with grilled tomato the day before. Finally, a super luxurious clam hot pot: rice is steamed with clam and a bonito broth, then topped with plump torigai plum and manju clams, as well as creamy sea urchin and a Japanese broccolini blossom for good measure. Simple, perfect."]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1573-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            136.6687752,36.5724877,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Yamanaka Onsen</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony described this area as "unlike anyplace I've ever been in Japan." Masa's good friend and pottery mentor, Haruo Konishi has a family hideaway here. They made iwana (char) caught that day in a mountain stream, Hokkaido scallops, wild Japanese boar, grilled fukinoto, and soba noodles with duck, green onion, and dashi sauce.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-9C27B0</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            136.3807957,36.2487575,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Ginza Sushi Ko Honten</name>
        <description>One of the BEST sushi places in the world. Masa learned here. They had seared horse mackerel over green onion and ginger, maguro (bluefin tuna), Japanese tiger prawn, octopus, fluke sashimi, striped jack, anago (sea eel) rolled in seaweed, and tamagoyaki (breaded shrimp eggs and fish paste)</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            139.761137,35.6713281,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Nasushiobara</name>
        <description><![CDATA[The rural town where Masa grew up. Tony and Masa visited his family (mom and daughter). His mother made motsuni, "a slow simmered stew of pork tripe, konnyaku, daikon, green onions, and miso," sashimi with freshly grated wasabi, uni, and otoro (tuna).]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1603-9C27B0</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            140.0460727,36.9616857,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Sugimura (Closed?)</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Masa's brother Kazuo had a restaurant in Nasushiobara called Sugimura. Could not find it on the map. They had "kimoyaki, eel liver dipped in a sauce of sake, soy, and mirin, and grilled low and slow over charcoal... insanely delicious custard of eel and egg, jacked with bean curd, bonito broth, and kelp... hitsumabushi, eel steamed, dressed, and grilled, over rice."]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-BDBDBD</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            140.0460727,36.9616857,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Kita Onsen（株）北温泉旅館</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony met with Masa's high school friends and had a soak in the hot spring, then ate sukiyaki (meat slowly cooked, tableside, in a broth), Tochigi beef with maitake (type of mushroom), and home-brewed sake]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1811-0288D1</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            139.9964294,37.1240272,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Mercado Central de Belo Horizonte</name>
        <description>Tony met with chef Leo Paixão, who trained under Joel Robuchon and now runs Glouton. They tried all sorts of fruits and veggies only found in Brazil.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1578-673AB7</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -43.9431479,-19.9230462,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Bar Da Lora</name>
        <description>Tony and Leon met with Ivo Faria, the “godfather” of mineiro cuisine at this restaurant inside the Mercado Central. They had beer, liver with jiló (a veggie like eggplant, only green and only edible when ripe).</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -43.9433615,-19.9227053,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Bar Do Careca</name>
        <description><![CDATA[A boteco, or neighborhood restaurant that serves beer. Tony met with Eduardo Maya, “self-taught gastronome,” and Luiz Otavio, a beverage tycoon who specializes in cachaça at Cachaça Vale Verde. They had "ox tongue cooked with basil, mint, and pepper" and "feijão tropeiro: beans, manioc flour smoked in cured meats" and fresh eggs.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -43.9471578,-19.8886712,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Meal with locals</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony had a meal cooked by Zora Santos, "a practitioner of old school Afro-Mineira cuisine." They had angu (cornmeal and milk cooked for hours), ora pro nobis (a native green, filled with protein), pork ribs.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1603-9C27B0</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -43.9036442,-19.893593,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Inhotim Museum</name>
        <description>Deep in the jungle, this contemporary art museum built by an eccentric visionary.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1636-0288D1</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -44.2196121,-20.1242111,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Meal with locals</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Meal on a family farm with a collection of chefs. They had "smoked pig's head with vegetables and chilies, native green beans called andu prepared with bacon and farofa" (toasted cassava flour). Also, "chicken in brown sauce baked in a clay pot, finished with the blood of chickens fresh killed this morning, served with pequi rice, farofa, and of course, cachaca."]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1603-9C27B0</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -43.6447287,-20.2866162,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Birosca S2</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony met with a group of women chefs to eat at this restaurant, including Bruna Martins, who owns the restaurant. Bruna only hires women to work there. They had "turkey neck, braised with butter and garlic, served with white beans, topped with kale and pork belly... ox hump pot-roast, served with mashed potatoes and farofa." While there, they had a scare when a drunk man in a stolen car was seen with a gun. The cameraman and producer dove on top of Tony to protect him, to which he said, "you know, you're NOT the secret service!"]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -43.909859,-19.914615,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Nono - O Rei do Caldo de Mocotó</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Open very late into the night, this place serves mocotó, "the ultimate in broke-ass, drunk-ass peasant food. Slow-cooked cow’s foot and/ or other bits, tender and tasty, and believe me, one of my favorites, especially at this hour. We opt for the elite version, served with raw quail egg."]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1517-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -43.9423485,-19.9209728,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Osteria dal 1931</name>
        <description>Tony ate by himself here, he had Chianti, prosciutto and artichoke hearts in olive oil, ravioli.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            12.4523864,41.8777402,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Gladiators</name>
        <description>Tony and Asia Argento had pasta for dinner ringside at a boxing match.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-FF5252</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            12.5759025,41.8567328,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name><![CDATA[L'Angolo degli amici (Closed)]]></name>
        <description><![CDATA[Former site of this restaurant, which translated to Friends' Corner.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-BDBDBD</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            12.2632805,41.7358442,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Simply Market</name>
        <description>Tony and Asia went shopping here for a lunch her sister prepared for them. They bought fava beans, cheese, and other goodies.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1578-673AB7</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            12.452808,41.96571,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Trattoria Morgana</name>
        <description>Tony had a meal with Abel Ferrara, film director known for Kings of New York and Bad Lieutenant, who now lives in Rome with his family. They had Roman pastas, snails, and  artichokes.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            12.5007067,41.8930283,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Bar Caffetteria</name>
        <description>Tony had espresso and a bomba, a type of Italian donut, for breakfast.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1534-795548</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            12.5598167,41.9293403,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Trattoria Settimio</name>
        <description>The restaurant that Tony and Asia visited in Rome that Tony refused to disclose the name of. </description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            12.4686495,41.8972949,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Palazzo dei Congressi</name>
        <description>Tony and Asia visited this huge structure, which was built originally to be a symbol of fascism.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1523-0288D1</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            12.4745454,41.8340588,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
    </Folder>
    <Folder>
      <name>Season 9</name>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Gish Bac</name>
        <description><![CDATA["Serves specialties from the city of Tlacolula de Matamoros in Oaxaca, Mexico," says Tony. He visited this place with UCLA Chicano Studies professor, Raul Hinojosa-Ojeda. They had black mole and barbacoa.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -118.3301621,34.0401044,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>La Reyna </name>
        <description><![CDATA[This is a cart that sells mulitas, "not quite a taco, not a quesadilla. More of a taco sandwich. First the tortilla goes on the grill, then marinated meat, cheese, then another tortilla. Flip and serve."]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1722-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -118.23213,34.0343929,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Cielito Lindo</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony met comedian Al Madrigal and editor of OC Weekly, Gustavo Arellano. They went to this place to get some taquitos, "rolled up, fried, smothered in avocado sauce, topped with chile guero, garlic, tomatillo, and cilantro." Also, a burrito with beans with machaca, spicy shredded beef, sauce, and cheese. ]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -118.2373849,34.0580033,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name><![CDATA[Trejo's Cantina - Hollywood]]></name>
        <description><![CDATA[Actor Danny Trejo's restaurant. Tony had an assortment of tacos just before they had their grand opening: "jidori chicken with chipotle cream sauce, some charred branzino with summer squash and sauteed poblano peppers, and crispy pork tacos with black garlic mole and some fat sacks of uni, and lots of healthy greens."]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -118.328981,34.0994871,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Mariscos Chente</name>
        <description>Tony had camarones borrachos (Drunken Shrimp) with 3 MMA fighters: Gilbert Melendez, Nick Diaz, and Nate Diaz.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -118.3612027,33.9447359,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Broken Spanish</name>
        <description>Fancy Mexican restaurant by Chef Ray Garcia. Chicharron cooked souvide, slow cooked lamb-neck tamales with oyster mushrooms and queso oaxaca, Okinawan sweet potato filled with pork, topped with piloncillo syrup with bread with foie gras and piloncillo.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -118.26352,34.043274,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Caña Rum Bar</name>
        <description>Tony had drinks with an ex-cop named Alex Salazar that admits he crossed lines and did bad things when he was a street cop.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1517-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -118.2632598,34.0441294,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Tacos Indiana</name>
        <description><![CDATA[A taco truck serving carne asada, the slow grilled marinated beef classic served as a burrito with rice and beans, or simply on a tortilla as a taco. Tacos lengua, beef tongue braised with garlic and onions. And tacos al pastor, stacked guajillo chili rubbed pork shoulder slices with your choice of toppings."]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1722-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -118.130185,34.0899406,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Ganbara</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony went on a poteo (bar crawl) with the famous chef Juan Mari Arzak and his daughter Elena. They ate a lot of pintxos and drank beer. They did not specify the places they visited except for this one, because this was Tony's favorite place to get pintxos, and the first place someone brought him to when he first visited the Basque area. Iberico ham with mushrooms on toast, crab tartlets, seared wild mushrooms and foie gras with egg yolk (house specialty, and Tony's favorite)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -1.9854917,43.3234111,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Albaola Itsas Kultur Faktoria</name>
        <description>Xabier Agote, Shipwright and founder of the Basque Maritime Museum, is working here to built a 16th century style Basque galleon.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1681-FF5252</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -1.9258421,43.3291617,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Elkano Kalea</name>
        <description>Tony and Xabier had Rock prawn (head and body cooked separately—head grilled and body served semi-ceviche), grilled squid with onion-green pepper sauce, cocochas (hake fish jowls or chins), and grilled turbot (this is the dish people travel to this restaurant to try)</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -1.9831582,43.3217683,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Arzak</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony sat with the Arzaks, who, he considers family. "The food is innovative, wildly creative, forward thinking, but always, ALWAYS Basque. Marinated prawns on lemongrass and mint with beetroot and crunchy krill, roast pigeon with mastic and potato... grilled hake jowls with teff seeds and almonds served in a bamboo leaf... grilled monkfish with a pecan paste and hieroglyphics of pumpkin and sweet pea... white tuna with green melon and a jackfruit sauce... squid with walnut-ginger paste, psyllium sauce with black tomato."]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -1.9492917,43.3214494,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Ostalapia</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony had a meal with Miray Girt, who was born in Spanish Basque country but raised in France.They discussed the differences between French and Spanish Basque foods. They had "ventrèche de thon, or tuna belly with tomato carpaccio; pigeon, roasted and then flambéed, served with a terrine or pâté of the same bird."]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -1.5972117,43.4004447,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Sociedad Aizepe</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony met with a group at this place. They discussed "txokos" or "private and historically all-male gastronomical societies, though that gender rule has changed with the times." The menu for the evening: "diced raw tuna, grilled prawns with green sauce" to start, then "for the main, fried hake cooked with txakoli and steamed clams."]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -1.9873812,43.323656,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Asador Etxebarri</name>
        <description><![CDATA["In every way, extraordinary" says Tony. He had lunch with his old friend Virginia Irizar, who runs a restaurant, and whose dad showed him San Sebastian for the first time. The chef of Etxebarri, Victor Arguinzoniz, makes everything himself from local ingredients. Tony had chorizo "served over a tiny little grill still smoking and infusing it with scent and flavor, grilled razor clams, beluga caviar... grilled and heaped over almond paste... perfectly cooked prawns. Line caught squid, grilled and served in its own ink. And king hell Galician beef chop, grilled."]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -2.5984691,43.1158721,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Casa Urola</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony ate here with Olatz González Abrisketa, a documentarian and professor of social anthropology at the University of the Basque Country. "Seared mushrooms with egg yolk and pine nuts... grilled tuna with marmitako sauce, a reference to a classic fishermen's stew;  peas in a consommé of Ibérico ham," and squid with a white bean cream. ]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -1.9844592,43.3233372,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Phosy Market</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony met with James Syhabout, a chef and restaurateur behind two-Michelin star restaurant Commis, in San Francisco. They had a bowl of khao piak sen, or Lao noodle soup, which is James' first dish he seeks out once he gets off the plane. The dish includes crispy sliced pork, blood cake, meat broth.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1578-673AB7</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            102.1234344,19.8777648,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Meal with locals</name>
        <description>Tony visited this small village in northern Laos. The villagers cooked him chicken and veggies.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1603-673AB7</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            103.7542606,21.1110895,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Boun Ork Phansa</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony visited during this Buddhist event that marks the end of Buddhist lent. There is a fire lantern festival, the symbolic casting away of one's sins. Tony watched a boat race on the Mekong River.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1668-FF5252</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            102.1387166,19.883285,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Villa Ban Lao Hotel</name>
        <description><![CDATA["During the Secret War, [this hotel] was the offices for USAID, America's foreign aid mission," says Tony. He had lunch here with the hotel owner, Mama Vahn, who made the meal, "an elaborate spread of dishes whose recipes are left over from imperial times." They had lon song, a fish from the Mekong River, cooked with shallots, garlic, chili, coconut milk, and pork; river crab, fish with pork grilled in banana leaves, ginger sauce, pork skin, and sticky rice.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-7CB342</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            102.1329634,19.8835797,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Meal with locals</name>
        <description>Tony had a meal with Chef James Syhabuot and his friends/family. They had aw lahm, which is made with wood ear mushrooms, dill, pepper wood (a key ingredient infused into the dish, which imparts flavors of star anise and white pepper), two types of lahm made with buffalo (one raw, one cooked), and leuat paeng, a dish made from raw buffalo blood and herbs.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1603-9C27B0</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            102.1387166,19.883285,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>UXO Lao</name>
        <description>Tony met with workers from this organization tasked with finding unexploded objects left behind by American forces during the Secret War and safely blowing them up. Only 0.5% of the country has been cleared of unexploded devices. Kids and adults have been maimed and dismembered by these bombs strewn about the countryside.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1853-FF5252</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            102.6143184,17.9812329,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Roosevelt Av - Jackson Heights</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Take the 7 train and get off at Roosevelt Ave. to find lots of awesome food stands. One place sells Ecuadorian food right at the exit to the subway, such as hornado, or "roast pork with sublime crispy skin straight from Heaven, morcilla, or blood sausage with potato cakes." The cart is called La Esquina de la Caserita.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1722-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -73.8909986,40.746739,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Yu Garden Dumplings (Closed)</name>
        <description>Tony met with Himanshu Suri, rapper and member of the Swet Shop Boys hip hop group, who is also known as Heems. They had an assortment of dumplings at this restaurant, which is now permanently closed.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-BDBDBD</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -73.8187599,40.7500238,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Geo Si Gi</name>
        <description><![CDATA[For great Chinese food in Flushing. Tony met with chefs Josh Smookler and Cosme Aguilar. They had galbi, or "short ribs marinated in soy, garlic, and sesame oil, then grilled." and gam ja tang, a soup made from pork neck bones.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -73.812025,40.7647333,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name><![CDATA[Neir's Tavern]]></name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony had a beer with Loycent “Loy” Gordon, the owner of the tavern, and New York City Fire Department lieutenant. The movie "Goodfellas" filmed scenes in this bar.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1879-FFD600</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -73.8635147,40.6898112,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Lhasa Fast Food</name>
        <description>Tony met with Hemms and his friend, attorney, and community organizer, Ali Najmi. They had thentuk, which is a hand torn noodle soup with chilies and ginger. Also, shaptra or chili-fried beef made of thinly sliced beef cooked with chili oil, soy, and Sichuan peppercorns; and sha momo, or steamed beef dumplings.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1640-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -73.891627,40.7471503,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Brisas Del Mar</name>
        <description>Tony had a meal with Josmar Trujillo, a writer and activist. They did not say what they had but it involved rice and beans and some kind of grilled meat.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -73.820536,40.584274,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Aqueduct Racetrack</name>
        <description>Tony met with his friend and author Laurie Woolever, who co-wrote his cookbook Appetites with him. They bet on some horses and ate Jamaican beef patties.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1601-FF5252</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -73.8330556,40.6716667,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Africana</name>
        <description><![CDATA[A Nigerian restaurant in Jamaica Queens, with chef Blessing Osagiede running the place. Tony ate here with Sarah K. Khan, a food & culture writer, filmmaker, and photographer.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -73.8059521,40.6947258,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>McMurdo Station</name>
        <description>Largest US base on Antarctica, and a tight knit community of researchers, scientists, carpenters, pilots, machine operators, and others who run the station. </description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1604-3949AB</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            166.6863449,-77.8418779,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Galley</name>
        <description>Tony had a meal with 2 women heavy machine operators.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            166.6680224,-77.8463906,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Mount Lister</name>
        <description>Tony went on a helicopter ride with pilot Ryan Skorecki, who flies scientists around the continent to remote areas. He pointed out Mount Lister from the sky.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1593-0288D1</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            162.683333,-78.066667,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Mount Erebus</name>
        <description>On the helicopter ride, they also saw Mount Erebus, the southernmost active volcano on Earth.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1593-0288D1</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            167.1523106,-77.5292912,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Cape Royds Adélie Penguin Rookery</name>
        <description>Tony visited this penguin colony of 2000 breeding pairs. He talked with marine ecologists Dr. David Ainley, who has been studying the colony for 20 years.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1743-3949AB</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            166.1639106,-77.5544849,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Lake Hoare</name>
        <description>One of the most oldest and legendary base camps. Everything comes in by helicopter. The manager at the camp is said to be the best cook on the continent. She made grilled pork tenderloin, grilled mahi sticks, shrimp marinated in chili sauce, homemade sourdough bread, roasted beet salad, edamame salad, roasted vegetables.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-3949AB</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            162.8818281,-77.6284658,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>South Pole</name>
        <description>Tony visited the Polar Plateau. It is 9000 feet above sea level. The altitude and extreme wind is incredibly harsh, dropping to below 50F. The base has the feel of a space station. </description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1523-3949AB</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            0.6961888,-72.2940091,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Mutrah Souq</name>
        <description>Tony and Aisha Stoby, PhD candidate of Middle Eastern art, strolled through this market and talked about the culture of Oman.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1578-673AB7</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            58.5630911,23.6193436,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Mutrah Corniche</name>
        <description><![CDATA["I love that word, corniche. I love any city with a corniche," said Tony.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1523-0288D1</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            58.5729325,23.622831,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Bait Al Luban Restaurant</name>
        <description><![CDATA["Dishes like pakora and kachori which both came back from India, chapati from East Africa, and shuwa, Oman's classic special event dish.... they slather a goat with a spicy paste consisting of cumin, coriander, red pepper, cinnamon, cardamom, and nutmeg. Then wrap the meat in palm or banana leaves, dig a hole, throw in some meat, and cover it up and leave underground for a day or two over hot coals."]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            58.5611465,23.6246197,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Al Hamra</name>
        <description><![CDATA[A catering business run by women whose profits go to funding children's education in rural areas. They cooked a meal of "kabuli laham, slow cooked goat in a rice pilaf scented with star anise. Musanif djaj, a local specialty, are pan seared dumplings stuffed with chicken, pepper, ginger, turmeric, and onions. And of course there's Omani bread with honey."]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1603-9C27B0</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            57.2875097,23.1025508,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Sharqiya Sands</name>
        <description>Tony camped out here in the desert and ate a meal with locals. They cooked the meal on the fire.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1765-0288D1</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            58.7222403,22.3999689,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name><![CDATA[Queen's Park Savannah]]></name>
        <description>Tony had fried snapper here at a place with many street food stands.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -61.5143677,10.6687426,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name><![CDATA[Ali's Doubles]]></name>
        <description><![CDATA[Everyone tells Tony he needs to try doubles. "Doubles are a Caribbean take on the Indian chana bhatura, two floppy, tender pieces of soft, Indian-style bread loaded with a wet heap of curried chickpeas, pepper sauce, and mango."]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -61.3646106,10.2702881,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Meal with locals</name>
        <description>Tony had a duck curry made by his host.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1603-9C27B0</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -61.5085625,10.6603196,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Meal with locals</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Bayshore is one of the priciest neighborhoods in the country. "I'm here as a guest of the Sabgavuds, a successful family of Lebanese Syrians," says Tony.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1603-9C27B0</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -61.5654353,10.6808265,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>A Cozinha Do Martinho</name>
        <description>Tony had fried sardines, Tripe Porto-style, and wine.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -8.5841637,41.1784859,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Real Companhia Velha</name>
        <description>Tony tried port and assorted cheeses, bread, pumpkin jam.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1578-673AB7</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -8.6009764,41.1327446,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Cervejaria Gazela - O Original Cachorrinho</name>
        <description>Tony had cachorros here, made of toasted bread, fresh pork sausage, cheese, and a spicy sauce. And fries</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1810-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -8.6075876,41.1448991,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Marisqueira Antiga</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony had an enormous platter of seafood consisting of "coastal shrimp, local oysters and crab, sea urchin, langoustine, gooseneck barnacles, whelks, and clams, and a salt-baked sea bass."]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1573-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -8.6908333,41.1819444,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Meal with locals</name>
        <description>Tony witnessed the town get together to slaughter a pig and cook it for a feast.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1603-9C27B0</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -8.6291053,41.1579438,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Café Restaurante O Afonso</name>
        <description>Tony had a francesinha (a sandwich made of sliced bread, steak, sausage, linguiça, cooked in a sauce of beer, port wine, spice, tomato, and a lot of cheese melted on top).</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -8.6217367,41.1526364,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
    </Folder>
    <Folder>
      <name>Season 10</name>
      <Placemark>
        <name>545 Whampoa Prawn Noodle</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony met with KF Seetoh, his guide in Singapore, "the guru behind the Makansutra guides and an advocate for the kind of democratic, affordable, casual chaos of the hawker world." They had prawn mi from this stand. ]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            103.854024,1.3234033,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Sabar Menanti II</name>
        <description>Tony met with Singaporean- Malay entertainer and producer Najip Ali for Lontong (rice cake, coconut gravy, vegetables and hardboiled egg) and Mee Siam (fried rice noodles with chili paste, prawns, bean sprouts, and a spicy sweet and sour gravy, fried bean curd, and egg).</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            103.858966,1.3030516,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Lorong 29 Geylang</name>
        <description>Tony had a meal with Sadir Varaket, Melanie Chan, and Tanya Andoor. They had fried oyster omelets and fried prawns with chili paste; bak chor mi, a fish ball noodle soup; and beef satay.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            103.8856631,1.3141795,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Guan Hoe Soon Restaurant</name>
        <description><![CDATA["The oldest Peranakan restaurant in Singapore, predating independence." They had a Laotian dish called ikam asam nana, a sour fish curry with pineapple; itek sio, a duck braised in tamarind and coriander; and okra sautéed with sambal.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            103.9012151,1.3132825,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Keng Eng Kee Seafood</name>
        <description>Tony had a meal with the family who runs this restaurant. They had pig trotters with black vinegar (and ginger, fried chilies, and asam), Hainan mixed vegetables (cabbage and glass noodles stir fried with bean curd, black mushrooms, pig skin, and shrimp).</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1573-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            103.8037037,1.2857843,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Outram Park Fried Kway Teow Mee</name>
        <description><![CDATA[One of Tony's favorite things to eat in Singapore is char kway teow. "Ordinarily this is a breakfast," Tony explains. "I eat it every time I'm in Singapore." It is made of crispy lard bits, cockles, shrimp paste, and noodles.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            103.845918,1.2854065,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Aiguille des Grands Montets</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony and Eric Ripert went skiing here in the French Alps, which Tony describes as a place he fears, but is allowing Eric to have "payback" for the torture Eric endured in Sichuan China.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1688-FF5252</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            6.9611111,45.9483333,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Restaurant Plan Joran</name>
        <description>While skiing in the French Alps, Tony and Eric Ripert stopped here. They had pan-seared foie gras, seared veal loin with a wild mushroom sauce and vegetable medley, a cheese course.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            6.9349326,45.9669197,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Crémerie du Glacier</name>
        <description><![CDATA["A special place at the bottom of the mountain," describes Tony. "croute with morilles, and cream, lots of cream....farcante: a big, heavy, albeit thoroughly delicious loaf of potato, bacon, dried fruit, and cream slowly steamed in a bain marie."]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            6.933092,45.97755,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Hôtel du Buet</name>
        <description>Time for more cheese. Tony and Eric had raclette and fondue here.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            6.9193533,46.0194881,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Boucherie du Mont Blanc - Chamonix (Francia)</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Eric Ripert met with Maurice Guillot, Eric's mentor at this butcher/cheese shop. They bought beef tenderloin to make steak au poivre, tomme de chevre, and saucisson.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1578-673AB7</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            6.867944,45.9219142,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>ChaChaCha</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Eric Ripert and mentor Maurice Guillot went to this wine & spirits store to purchase champagne, white burgundy, and cognac.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1578-673AB7</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            6.865704,45.9197015,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Peloton de gendarmerie de haute montagne (PGHM)</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Eric's dream as a kid was to work as a park ranger, so they met with a lady named Sonia Popoff who does this for a living. "She's who you call when things are really bad," says Tony. They rescue skiiers who injure themselves on the mountain.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1558-FF5252</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            6.6829186,45.2032935,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Farmhouse Maison Rosset</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony hopped the border to Italy because he craved pasta in the Aoeste Valley. They had gnocchi with beet root fondue, ravioli with tomato sauce, creamy polenta with braised beef. Tony, Eric, and host played feur lane, a game where "you try to hit that tiny polished stone with that stick as far as you can."]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            7.4701072,45.7406127,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Rue80</name>
        <description>Tony had drinks with Shina Peller, owner of Club Quilox, (a music venue) and Banky Wellington, record label owner</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1602-7CB342</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            3.4286297,6.4258949,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name><![CDATA[Iya-Eba Restaurant & Bar]]></name>
        <description>Tony had spicy pepper soup with journalist  Kadaria Ahmed</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            3.4046635,6.4470421,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Computer Village</name>
        <description>Tony met with an economics expert to talk about the financial ecosystem of this marketplace. Young people learn to take apart and fix phones for a living.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1684-0288D1</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            3.3404658,6.5962459,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Stellas Kitchen</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony visited this restaurant to have pounded yams, egusi soup, "a stew of goat meat, melon seeds, fish stock, and chilies."]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            3.3403546,6.5949037,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>New Afrika Shrine</name>
        <description>Tony met the owner of this musical venue </description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1637-FBC02D</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            3.357059,6.6228724,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Central Mosque - Hausa Community Agege</name>
        <description>Tony met with His Royal Highness, Alhaji Musa Muhammadu Dogonkadai, Sarkin Hausawan Agege. They had masa (griddle cakes made from sticky rice, sugar, potash—a mineral-rich salt), fura (millet and milk compote), danwake (bean-flour dumplings served with tomatoes), moringa salad, kuli-kuli powder (ground peanut).</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-9C27B0</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            3.3255237,6.6226604,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Yakoyo Food Restaurant</name>
        <description>Traditional Nigerian foods such as ewedu (jute leaf) soup with crayfish, chilies, and locust beans; jollof rice (cooked in tomato sauce); goat; pounded yam.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            3.3521715,6.5049242,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Andela Nigeria</name>
        <description>Tony visited this training program where people are taught coding and software engineering.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1726-0288D1</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            3.3778801,6.5021747,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Bloomfield Park</name>
        <description>Tony played bocce ball and had a picnic of sausage and peppers and got beat by a 103-year old.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1747-FF5252</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -79.9539122,40.4628886,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Squirrel Hill Cafe</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony had beer and a burger with author Stewart O'Nan. ]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1530-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -79.9226711,40.4378655,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Pittsburgh</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony had "racks of pork rib, grilled hearts of escarole and turnips, a sauce made from the pork drippings, and four types of sausage" with Chefs Justin Severeno and Sonja Finn.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1603-9C27B0</styleUrl>
